content.description: As the name implies there is a thin seam that defines the start to this ultra thin slab route. Prepare for patience fraying, continously difficult moves that eventually let up to V2 near the tope. Truly the gift that keeps on giving. To my knowlege this route has never been bouldered.
content.location: The obvious seam in the middle of the west face.

content.description: This route starts on the left side of the arete and crosses over to the right near the top. Not sure if this route has ever been bouldered without a rope.
content.location: Northwest corner of "Agony of DaFeet Rock.

content.description: Yet another miserably thin slab route. To my knowlege this route has not been bouldered.
content.location: Located on the west face in between "NW Arete" & "Seam Stress".

content.description: This slabby route is just right of the NW Arete route. Climb a smooth slab that keeps on giving. Curt Love & I both bouldered this route in 1999.
content.location: First route to the right of the NW Arete route on the west face of "Agony of DaFeet Rock".

content.description: This route starts on a series of wavy ramps just right of "Seam Stress". Once again like the nearby routes the difficulties continue to near the summit on thin slabby climbing. Curt Love & I bouldered this route in 1999.
content.location: Five feet right of the start to "Seam Stress".

pathTokens: Land Of The Way Too High Boulders, The

content.description: "Agony of Da-Feet" offers very technical, high ball, slabby routes on the west face. There is a vertical face face route on the north west corner. This rock is 30'+ tall and has bolts for top roping. Potential for more routes likewise.
